physicalObject: tall white and gold Kirin beer can
explanation: Cylinder diameter is close, but the height is much greater (tall 500 ml format). Palm cannot cover as much of the side and balance feels more top-heavy, so outline similarity is only moderate.
Slender rod (~1 cm Ø) instead of a 6 cm cylinder; requires fingertip pinch rather than full-hand wrap, completely breaking the expected power-grip outline.

physicalObject: silver and black retractable ballpoint pen
explanation: Same mismatch as the fine-liner: extremely small diameter and elongated stick shape offer none of the expected palm contact or cylindrical bulk.
Irregular sphere roughly 4–5 cm across, not a rigid cylinder; no flat sidewalls for palm wrap, so outline cues are absent.
Soft, compressible ball with no cylindrical geometry; shape collapses on grip, providing none of the expected outline.
General cylindrical form is present, but cup is tapered, open-topped, and wider than 6 cm at the rim. Thin flexible walls feel hollow and change grip dynamics, partially delivering outline cues.
Paper cup shares overall diameter range but has taper and compressible walls. Lack of rigid metal edge and differing height reduce fidelity of palm contact and outline.
Long thin handle affords a pinch grip, not a cylindrical wrap. Spoon bowl introduces asymmetry; outline similarity is negligible.
Handle is narrow and flat; overall shape is far from a 6 cm diameter cylinder, preventing the expected power-grip geometry.
Roughly cylindrical but much smaller (~4 cm Ø) and covered in blocky protrusions. Hard to achieve smooth palm contact; only a faint resemblance to the intended outline.
Highly irregular, non-cylindrical shape with protruding ears and facets; cannot mimic the smooth 6 cm cylinder outline in any meaningful way.
Large cylindrical can lacks any narrow, flat handle section; size and grip affordances differ drastically from a spoon’s flat handle.

physicalObject: tall white and gold beer can
explanation: Even bulkier cylinder than the small can; no flat, narrow handle portion, so outline is entirely mismatched.
Pen provides a slender stem to pinch, but it is round and much thinner than a spoon’s flat handle, giving limited fidelity to the expected outline.
Similar issues to the fine-liner: cylindrical, narrow barrel; no flat faces, so pinch feels quite different from a flat spoon handle.
Irregular, compressible sphere offers none of the elongated, flat handle outline required.
Soft amorphous ball; completely lacks a defined handle or flat gripping surface akin to a spoon.
Wide cylindrical cup requires whole-hand grip on rim; no flat, narrow handle geometry comparable to the virtual spoon.
Same mismatch as plastic cup—large open cylinder, no slender flat handle to pinch.
Provides a true spoon outline with a mostly flattened, slightly tapering handle that can be comfortably pinched; though thinner and slightly curved, overall shape supports expected grips well.
Nearly identical geometry: flat, moderately wide wooden handle and a shallow bowl; affords the same pinch and rotation patterns, delivering excellent outline fidelity.
Blocky cubic shape with no handle; outline bears no resemblance to a spoon’s flat handle.
Irregular animal shape without any flat, elongated handle segment; offers none of the required outline characteristics.
The can is made of thin aluminum (high thermal conductivity). At room temperature it feels noticeably cool-cold on first touch, the opposite of the neutral-warm wood sensation expected.
Same aluminum material as the smaller can, so it delivers a distinctly cool metallic feel, which conflicts strongly with the desired neutral-warm wooden temperature.

The pen barrel appears to be thin plastic. Plastic is moderately insulating and can reach skin temperature quickly, but its initial touch is usually cooler than wood and lacks the subtle organic warmth of bamboo.
The main barrel looks metallic, giving a cool sensation on contact. This coolness diverges from the neutral-warm expectation.

Paper is highly insulating and generally feels neutral to touch, closer to wood than metal. However, the thin, airy crumpled form provides minimal continuous contact surface, so the perceived temperature is inconsistent.

Soft tissue is even more insulating than standard paper and quickly feels body-temperature, producing a reasonably neutral-warm impression. The fluffy structure still causes uneven contact, but thermally it is closer to bamboo than plastic or metal.

The thin PET/PP plastic walls initially feel slightly cool but warm up fast due to low conductivity. This yields a near-neutral feel, though it lacks the subtle organic warmth that wood naturally provides.

Paperboard is a good thermal insulator and typically feels at ambient/hand temperature almost immediately, generating a neutral-warm sensation fairly close to bamboo, though still a bit drier in feel.
Stainless steel is highly conductive and feels cold on contact in normal indoor conditions, the exact opposite of the expected neutral-warm wood temperature.
This object is visibly made of unfinished wood, matching bamboo’s low thermal conductivity and immediate neutral-warm touch almost perfectly, delivering the intended temperature cue.
ABS plastic blocks initially feel cooler than wood but warmer than metal; they warm somewhat slowly in small contact areas. Overall only a partial match to the desired neutral-warm feel.
Made of the same small ABS plastic bricks as the hamburger, giving a slightly cool initial touch that never quite reaches the gentle warmth characteristic of bamboo.

physicalObject: small beige beverage can with pull-tab
explanation: The pull-tab does give a short rigid travel and metallic stop, but it is positioned on a horizontal surface and requires a lever-like motion, not the axial thumb plunge at the back of a pen. The bulky cylindrical body also prevents a realistic tripod writing grip.
Same limitations as the small can: lever action on a top surface, large diameter, difficult to hold like a pen. Does not reproduce a small plunger with a firm plastic knock.

The form factor allows an authentic tripod grip and thumb reach to the back, but the rear cap is fixed—there is essentially no axial travel or audible click. Provides an immediate hard surface rather than a short motion with a firm stop, so the key interactive element is missing.

The pen can be held exactly like the virtual technical pen and has a rear clicker, but the mechanism is spring-loaded and travels several millimetres with a soft rebound and two-stage latch, not a single non-springed firm stop. Provides partial but imperfect match.
Entirely soft and compliant; no rigid plunger, no defined stop, no pen-like grip possible.
Extremely soft, deformable, and shapeless; cannot simulate any firm plunger or pen grip.
Large diameter, no axial plunger, rim flexes rather than giving a crisp stop. Does not support finger-tip plunger action.
Paper rim collapses under thumb pressure; no rigid travel or click. Shape prevents pen-like grip.

The handle end can be pressed with the thumb and gives an immediate immovable stop, mimicking firmness, but there is zero travel and the handle is too wide/flat for a realistic pen plunger experience.
Even bulkier than the metal spoon; offers only a hard surface with no displacement. Wood absorbs sound, so no crisp plastic knock. Poor grip resemblance.
Studs are rigid and give firm resistance, but there is no axial motion or plunger. Object is blocky and cannot be held in a pen-like grip.
Irregular shape, no movable parts matching a plunger, and cannot be held like a pen. Provides no relevant haptic interaction.

Although cylindrical, the can’s diameter is many times thicker than a pen (see Image 0, upper left). It prevents a comfortable tripod writing grip and feels like grasping a drink container rather than a slim shaft.

physicalObject: tall white and gold Kirin beer can
explanation: Same issues as the smaller can but even longer and heavier; far too large to simulate the narrow barrel of a technical pen.
Visually almost identical to the virtual pen: matching diameter, straight cylindrical body, and correct length. Supports natural tripod grip at the tip.

physicalObject: silver and black retractable ballpoint pen
explanation: Slightly thicker mid-barrel and has a clip bulge, but overall offers a slim, pen-like cylindrical shaft that can be held exactly like the virtual technical pen.
Irregular, compressible blob with no shaft; cannot approximate a slim cylinder or allow controlled writing grip.
Soft, amorphous ball (Image 0, bottom right). No rigid cylindrical form; impossible to mimic a pen’s outline.
Large tapered cylinder meant for holding beverages, not a slim shaft. Diameter far exceeds finger-tip span for a pen grip.
Similar to the plastic cup—wide, conical shape with no resemblance to a pen’s slender outline.
The handle is narrow but flattened and widens into a bowl at one end (Image 1, bottom left). Provides some slim segment but overall outline deviates noticeably from a uniform cylinder.
Handle is wider and rectangular in cross-section; wood edges are flat, and the front bowl is bulky. Only partially slim, so outline mismatch is evident.
Blocky cubic object with studs; no elongated shaft whatsoever, utterly fails to evoke a pen-like outline.
Irregular multi-lobed shape with protruding ears; cannot be grasped or felt as a slim cylindrical form akin to a technical pen.

physicalObject: small beige beverage can with Asian script label
explanation: The pull-tab offers only a short metal hinge movement and, once bent, does not reset with spring force. Travel, elastic feel, and repeatability of a 4 mm spring plunger are missing.

physicalObject: tall white and gold Kirin beer can
explanation: Same hinged pull-tab limitation as the small can; no spring return or detent click cycle. The large diameter and weight also prevent pen-like twirling.
This pen has a rigid, non-moving end cap. There is no spring, plunger travel, or audible detent—core interactive mechanism is absent.

physicalObject: silver and black retractable ballpoint pen
explanation: Visibly includes a spring-loaded top plunger with ~4 mm travel that produces a crisp audible click and snap-back, perfectly matching the described fidget-click experience and barrel size.
Paper compresses and springs back softly but lacks a confined 4 mm stroke, firm resistance, or a detent click; feedback is vague, not pen-like.
Very soft and floppy; provides no distinct travel limit or snap. The interaction feels nothing like a spring-loaded pen plunger.
Rim flexes but with large, mushy displacement and no detent or audible click. Shape is bulky and cannot be twirled in a tripod grip.
Paper lip bends without spring snap or defined stroke; interaction is squishy and does not reset crisply like a pen plunger.
Completely rigid; no movable element to press. Provides none of the required spring-loaded feedback.
Rigid wood with no moving parts; zero resemblance to a clickable pen mechanism.
Pressing the top bricks gives slight frictional movement or separation rather than a spring return; lacks defined 4 mm travel and snap detent.
Solid interlocked bricks; ears do not flex with spring action. No plunger, no click, no resemblance to the described interactive cycle.
Although cylindrical, the can is far wider than a pen barrel; cannot be held in a tripod grip nor twirled like a slim shaft.
Extreme diameter and weight make the outline completely unlike the slim cylindrical shaft of a pen.
Nearly identical size, diameter, and cylindrical form; fits natural tripod grip and feels like the virtual pen’s slender barrel.

physicalObject: silver and black retractable ballpoint pen
explanation: Matches the virtual object exactly—same slim cylindrical barrel and proportions; perfect outline correspondence.
Irregular spherical shape with no slender shaft; cannot mimic pen outline at all.
Soft, amorphous ball—no resemblance to a slim cylindrical pen.
Cylindrical but far too wide; cannot be grasped like a pen or provide the slender shaft feel.
Similar issues as the plastic cup—diameter and taper make the outline unlike a pen’s slim barrel.
Handle is long and slim but flat rather than cylindrical, and bowl at end disrupts uniform shaft; partially matches outline.
Handle offers some slender length, but it is thicker, rectangular, and terminates in a large bowl, reducing fidelity to a pen’s uniform cylindrical outline.
Blocky, squat form bears no resemblance to a slim cylindrical shaft.
Irregular animal shape; no continuous slim cylinder present—cannot replicate pen outline.
